Classes/AWSComprehend.html#/c:objc(cs)AW.name: -createFlywheel:
Classes/AWSComprehend.html#/c:objc(cs)AW.abstract:
A flywheel is an Amazon Web Services resource that orchestrates the ongoing training of a model for custom classification or custom entity recognition. You can create a flywheel to start with an existing trained model, or Comprehend can create and train a new model.

When you create the flywheel, Comprehend creates a data lake in your account. The data lake holds the training data and test data for all versions of the model.

To use a flywheel with an existing trained model, you specify the active model version. Comprehend copies the model’s training data and test data into the flywheel’s data lake.

To use the flywheel with a new model, you need to provide a dataset for training data (and optional test data) when you create the flywheel.

For more information about flywheels, see Flywheel overview in the Amazon Comprehend Developer Guide.

Classes/AWSComprehend.html#/c:objc(cs)AW.name: -deleteDocumentClassifier:
Classes/AWSComprehend.html#/c:objc(cs)AW.abstract:
Deletes a previously created document classifier

Only those classifiers that are in terminated states (IN_ERROR, TRAINED) will be deleted. If an active inference job is using the model, a ResourceInUseException will be returned.

This is an asynchronous action that puts the classifier into a DELETING state, and it is then removed by a background job. Once removed, the classifier disappears from your account and is no longer available for use.

Classes/AWSComprehend.html#/c:objc(cs)AW.name: -stopDominantLanguageDetectionJob:
Classes/AWSComprehend.html#/c:objc(cs)AW.abstract:
Stops a dominant language detection job in progress.

If the job state is IN_PROGRESS the job is marked for termination and put into the STOP_REQUESTED state. If the job completes before it can be stopped, it is put into the COMPLETED state; otherwise the job is stopped and put into the STOPPED state.

If the job is in the COMPLETED or FAILED state when you call the StopDominantLanguageDetectionJob operation, the operation returns a 400 Internal Request Exception.

When a job is stopped, any documents already processed are written to the output location.

Classes/AWSComprehendEntityRecognizerInp.name: dataFormat
Classes/AWSComprehendEntityRecognizerInp.abstract:
The format of your training data:

  • COMPREHEND_CSV: A CSV file that supplements your training documents. The CSV file contains information about the custom entities that your trained model will detect. The required format of the file depends on whether you are providing annotations or an entity list.

    If you use this value, you must provide your CSV file by using either the Annotations or EntityList parameters. You must provide your training documents by using the Documents parameter.

  • AUGMENTED_MANIFEST: A labeled dataset that is produced by Amazon SageMaker Ground Truth. This file is in JSON lines format. Each line is a complete JSON object that contains a training document and its labels. Each label annotates a named entity in the training document.

    If you use this value, you must provide the AugmentedManifests parameter in your request.

If you don’t specify a value, Amazon Comprehend uses COMPREHEND_CSV as the default.

Classes/AWSComprehendEntityRecognizerInp.name: documents

A maximum of 25 entity types can be used at one time to train an entity recognizer. Entity types must not contain the following invalid characters: \n (line break), \n (escaped line break), \r (carriage return), \r (escaped carriage return), \t (tab), \t (escaped tab), space, and , (comma).

Classes/AWSComprehendEntityRecognizerEva.name: precision

Classes/AWSComprehendEntityRecognizerEva.name: recall

Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentReaderConfi.name: documentReadMode

Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentReaderConfi.name: featureTypes

Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassifierP.name: status
Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassifierP.abstract:
The status of the document classifier. If the status is TRAINED the classifier is ready to use. If the status is TRAINED_WITH_WARNINGS the classifier training succeeded, but you should review the warnings returned in the CreateDocumentClassifier response.

If the status is FAILED you can see additional information about why the classifier wasn’t trained in the Message field.

Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassifierO.name: s3Uri
Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassifierO.abstract:
When you use the OutputDataConfig object while creating a custom classifier, you specify the Amazon S3 location where you want to write the confusion matrix and other output files. The URI must be in the same Region as the API endpoint that you are calling. The location is used as the prefix for the actual location of this output file.

When the custom classifier job is finished, the service creates the output file in a directory specific to the job. The S3Uri field contains the location of the output file, called output.tar.gz. It is a compressed archive that contains the confusion matrix.

Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassifierI.name: augmentedManifests
Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassifierI.abstract:
A list of augmented manifest files that provide training data for your custom model. An augmented manifest file is a labeled dataset that is produced by Amazon SageMaker Ground Truth.

This parameter is required if you set DataFormat to AUGMENTED_MANIFEST.

Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassifierI.name: dataFormat
Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassifierI.abstract:
The format of your training data:

  • COMPREHEND_CSV: A two-column CSV file, where labels are provided in the first column, and documents are provided in the second. If you use this value, you must provide the S3Uri parameter in your request.

  • AUGMENTED_MANIFEST: A labeled dataset that is produced by Amazon SageMaker Ground Truth. This file is in JSON lines format. Each line is a complete JSON object that contains a training document and its associated labels.

    If you use this value, you must provide the AugmentedManifests parameter in your request.

If you don’t specify a value, Amazon Comprehend uses COMPREHEND_CSV as the default.

Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassifierI.name: documentReaderConfig
Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassifierI.abstract:
Provides configuration parameters to override the default actions for extracting text from PDF documents and image files.

By default, Amazon Comprehend performs the following actions to extract text from files, based on the input file type:

  • Word files - Amazon Comprehend parser extracts the text.

  • Digital PDF files - Amazon Comprehend parser extracts the text.

  • Image files and scanned PDF files - Amazon Comprehend uses the Amazon Textract DetectDocumentText API to extract the text.

DocumentReaderConfig does not apply to plain text files or Word files.

For image files and PDF documents, you can override these default actions using the fields listed below. For more information, see Setting text extraction options in the Comprehend Developer Guide.

Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassifierI.name: documentType
Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassifierI.abstract: The type of input documents for training the model. Provide plain-text documents to create a plain-text model, and provide semi-structured documents to create a native model.

Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassifierI.name: documents
Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassifierI.abstract: The S3 location of the training documents. This parameter is required in a request to create a native classifier model.

Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassifierI.name: labelDelimiter
Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassifierI.abstract: Indicates the delimiter used to separate each label for training a multi-label classifier. The default delimiter between labels is a pipe (|). You can use a different character as a delimiter (if it’s an allowed character) by specifying it under Delimiter for labels. If the training documents use a delimiter other than the default or the delimiter you specify, the labels on that line will be combined to make a single unique label, such as LABELLABELLABEL.

Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassifierI.name: s3Uri
Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassifierI.abstract:
The Amazon S3 URI for the input data. The S3 bucket must be in the same Region as the API endpoint that you are calling. The URI can point to a single input file or it can provide the prefix for a collection of input files.

For example, if you use the URI S3://bucketName/prefix, if the prefix is a single file, Amazon Comprehend uses that file as input. If more than one file begins with the prefix, Amazon Comprehend uses all of them as input.

This parameter is required if you set DataFormat to COMPREHEND_CSV.

Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassificat.name: jobArn
Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassificat.abstract:
The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the document classification job. It is a unique, fully qualified identifier for the job. It includes the Amazon Web Services account, Amazon Web Services Region, and the job ID. The format of the ARN is as follows:

arn:<partition>:comprehend:<region>:<account-id>:document-classification-job/<job-id>

The following is an example job ARN:

arn:aws:comprehend:us-west-2:111122223333:document-classification-job/1234abcd12ab34cd56ef1234567890ab

Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassificat.name: jobId
Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassificat.abstract: The identifier assigned to the document classification job.

Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassificat.name: jobName
Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassificat.abstract: The name that you assigned to the document classification job.

Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassificat.name: jobStatus
Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassificat.abstract: The current status of the document classification job. If the status is FAILED, the Message field shows the reason for the failure.

Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassificat.name: message
Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassificat.abstract: A description of the status of the job.

Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassificat.name: outputDataConfig
Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassificat.abstract: The output data configuration that you supplied when you created the document classification job.

Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassificat.name: submitTime
Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassificat.abstract: The time that the document classification job was submitted for processing.

Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassificat.name: volumeKmsKeyId
Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassificat.abstract:
ID for the Amazon Web Services Key Management Service (KMS) key that Amazon Comprehend uses to encrypt data on the storage volume attached to the ML compute instance(s) that process the analysis job. The VolumeKmsKeyId can be either of the following formats:

  • KMS Key ID: "1234abcd-12ab-34cd-56ef-1234567890ab"

  • Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of a KMS Key: "arn:aws:kms:us-west-2:111122223333:key/1234abcd-12ab-34cd-56ef-1234567890ab"

Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassificat.name: vpcConfig
Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassificat.abstract: Configuration parameters for a private Virtual Private Cloud (VPC) containing the resources you are using for your document classification job. For more information, see Amazon VPC.

Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassificat.name: jobName
Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassificat.abstract: Filters on the name of the job.

Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassificat.name: jobStatus
Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassificat.abstract: Filters the list based on job status. Returns only jobs with the specified status.

Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassificat.name: submitTimeAfter
Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassificat.abstract: Filters the list of jobs based on the time that the job was submitted for processing. Returns only jobs submitted after the specified time. Jobs are returned in descending order, newest to oldest.

Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassificat.name: submitTimeBefore
Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassificat.abstract: Filters the list of jobs based on the time that the job was submitted for processing. Returns only jobs submitted before the specified time. Jobs are returned in ascending order, oldest to newest.

Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassificat.name: labels
Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassificat.abstract: One or more labels to associate with the custom classifier.

Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassificat.name: mode
Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClassificat.abstract: Classification mode indicates whether the documents are MULTI_CLASS or MULTI_LABEL.

Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClass.html#.name: page
Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClass.html#.abstract: Page number in the input document. This field is present in the response only if your request includes the Byte parameter.

Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClass.html#.name: score
Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentClass.html#.abstract: The confidence score that Amazon Comprehend has this class correctly attributed.

Classes/AWSComprehendDetectSyntaxRespons.abstract: A collection of syntax tokens describing the text. For each token, the response provides the text, the token type, where the text begins and ends, and the level of confidence that Amazon Comprehend has that the token is correct. For a list of token types, see Syntax in the Comprehend Developer Guide.

Classes/AWSComprehendDetectSyntaxRequest.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSComprehendDetectSyntaxRequest.abstract: The language code of the input documents. You can specify any of the following languages supported by Amazon Comprehend: German (“de”), English (“en”), Spanish (“es”), French (“fr”), Italian (“it”), or Portuguese (“pt”).

Classes/AWSComprehendDetectSyntaxRequest.name: text
Classes/AWSComprehendDetectSyntaxRequest.abstract: A UTF-8 string. The maximum string size is 5 KB.

Classes/AWSComprehendDetectSentimentResp.name: sentiment
Classes/AWSComprehendDetectSentimentResp.abstract: The inferred sentiment that Amazon Comprehend has the highest level of confidence in.

Classes/AWSComprehendDetectSentimentResp.name: sentimentScore
Classes/AWSComprehendDetectSentimentResp.abstract: An object that lists the sentiments, and their corresponding confidence levels.

Classes/AWSComprehendDetectSentimentRequ.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSComprehendDetectSentimentRequ.abstract: The language of the input documents. You can specify any of the primary languages supported by Amazon Comprehend. All documents must be in the same language.

Classes/AWSComprehendDetectSentimentRequ.name: text
Classes/AWSComprehendDetectSentimentRequ.abstract: A UTF-8 text string. The maximum string size is 5 KB.

Classes/AWSComprehendDetectPiiEntitiesRe.name: entities
Classes/AWSComprehendDetectPiiEntitiesRe.abstract: A collection of PII entities identified in the input text. For each entity, the response provides the entity type, where the entity text begins and ends, and the level of confidence that Amazon Comprehend has in the detection.

Classes/AWSComprehendDetectPiiEntitiesRe.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSComprehendDetectPiiEntitiesRe.abstract: The language of the input documents. Currently, English is the only valid language.

Classes/AWSComprehendDetectPiiEntitiesRe.name: text
Classes/AWSComprehendDetectPiiEntitiesRe.abstract: A UTF-8 text string. The maximum string size is 100 KB.

Classes/AWSComprehendDetectKeyPhrasesRes.name: keyPhrases
Classes/AWSComprehendDetectKeyPhrasesRes.abstract: A collection of key phrases that Amazon Comprehend identified in the input text. For each key phrase, the response provides the text of the key phrase, where the key phrase begins and ends, and the level of confidence that Amazon Comprehend has in the accuracy of the detection.

Classes/AWSComprehendDetectKeyPhrasesReq.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSComprehendDetectKeyPhrasesReq.abstract: The language of the input documents. You can specify any of the primary languages supported by Amazon Comprehend. All documents must be in the same language.

Classes/AWSComprehendDetectKeyPhrasesReq.name: text
Classes/AWSComprehendDetectKeyPhrasesReq.abstract: A UTF-8 text string. The string must contain less than 100 KB of UTF-8 encoded characters.

Classes/AWSComprehendDetectEntitiesRespo.name: blocks
Classes/AWSComprehendDetectEntitiesRespo.abstract:
Information about each block of text in the input document. Blocks are nested. A page block contains a block for each line of text, which contains a block for each word.

The Block content for a Word input document does not include a Geometry field.

The Block field is not present in the response for plain-text inputs.

Classes/AWSComprehendDetectEntitiesRespo.name: documentMetadata
Classes/AWSComprehendDetectEntitiesRespo.abstract: Information about the document, discovered during text extraction. This field is present in the response only if your request used the Byte parameter.

Classes/AWSComprehendDetectEntitiesRespo.name: documentType
Classes/AWSComprehendDetectEntitiesRespo.abstract: The document type for each page in the input document. This field is present in the response only if your request used the Byte parameter.

Classes/AWSComprehendDetectEntitiesRespo.name: entities
Classes/AWSComprehendDetectEntitiesRespo.abstract:
A collection of entities identified in the input text. For each entity, the response provides the entity text, entity type, where the entity text begins and ends, and the level of confidence that Amazon Comprehend has in the detection.

If your request uses a custom entity recognition model, Amazon Comprehend detects the entities that the model is trained to recognize. Otherwise, it detects the default entity types. For a list of default entity types, see Entities in the Comprehend Developer Guide.

Classes/AWSComprehendDetectEntitiesRespo.name: errors
Classes/AWSComprehendDetectEntitiesRespo.abstract: Page-level errors that the system detected while processing the input document. The field is empty if the system encountered no errors.

Classes/AWSComprehendDetectEntitiesReque.name: bytes
Classes/AWSComprehendDetectEntitiesReque.abstract:
This field applies only when you use a custom entity recognition model that was trained with PDF annotations. For other cases, enter your text input in the Text field.

Use the Bytes parameter to input a text, PDF, Word or image file. Using a plain-text file in the Bytes parameter is equivelent to using the Text parameter (the Entities field in the response is identical).

You can also use the Bytes parameter to input an Amazon Textract DetectDocumentText or AnalyzeDocument output file.

Provide the input document as a sequence of base64-encoded bytes. If your code uses an Amazon Web Services SDK to detect entities, the SDK may encode the document file bytes for you.

The maximum length of this field depends on the input document type. For details, see Inputs for real-time custom analysis in the Comprehend Developer Guide.

If you use the Bytes parameter, do not use the Text parameter.

Classes/AWSComprehendDetectEntitiesReque.name: documentReaderConfig
Classes/AWSComprehendDetectEntitiesReque.abstract: Provides configuration parameters to override the default actions for extracting text from PDF documents and image files.

Classes/AWSComprehendDetectEntitiesReque.name: endpointArn
Classes/AWSComprehendDetectEntitiesReque.abstract:
The Amazon Resource Name of an endpoint that is associated with a custom entity recognition model. Provide an endpoint if you want to detect entities by using your own custom model instead of the default model that is used by Amazon Comprehend.

If you specify an endpoint, Amazon Comprehend uses the language of your custom model, and it ignores any language code that you provide in your request.

For information about endpoints, see Managing endpoints.

Classes/AWSComprehendDetectEntitiesReque.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSComprehendDetectEntitiesReque.abstract:
The language of the input documents. You can specify any of the primary languages supported by Amazon Comprehend. If your request includes the endpoint for a custom entity recognition model, Amazon Comprehend uses the language of your custom model, and it ignores any language code that you specify here.

All input documents must be in the same language.

Classes/AWSComprehendDetectEntitiesReque.name: text
Classes/AWSComprehendDetectEntitiesReque.abstract: A UTF-8 text string. The maximum string size is 100 KB. If you enter text using this parameter, do not use the Bytes parameter.

Classes/AWSComprehendDetectDominantLangu.name: languages
Classes/AWSComprehendDetectDominantLangu.abstract:
Array of languages that Amazon Comprehend detected in the input text. The array is sorted in descending order of the score (the dominant language is always the first element in the array).

For each language, the response returns the RFC 5646 language code and the level of confidence that Amazon Comprehend has in the accuracy of its inference. For more information about RFC 5646, see Tags for Identifying Languages on the IETF Tools web site.

Classes/AWSComprehendDetectDominantLangu.name: text
Classes/AWSComprehendDetectDominantLangu.abstract: A UTF-8 text string. The string must contain at least 20 characters. The maximum string size is 100 KB.

Classes/AWSComprehendDeleteDocumentClass.abstract: The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) that identifies the document classifier.

Classes/AWSComprehendDatasetProperties.h.abstract: The S3 URI where the dataset is stored.

Classes/AWSComprehendDatasetProperties.h.name: datasetType
Classes/AWSComprehendDatasetProperties.h.abstract: The dataset type (training data or test data).

Classes/AWSComprehendDatasetInputDataCon.name: augmentedManifests
Classes/AWSComprehendDatasetInputDataCon.abstract: A list of augmented manifest files that provide training data for your custom model. An augmented manifest file is a labeled dataset that is produced by Amazon SageMaker Ground Truth.

Classes/AWSComprehendDatasetInputDataCon.abstract:
COMPREHEND_CSV: The data format is a two-column CSV file, where the first column contains labels and the second column contains documents.

AUGMENTED_MANIFEST: The data format

Classes/AWSComprehendDatasetInputDataCon.name: entityRecognizerInputDataConfig

Classes/AWSComprehendDatasetEntityRecogn.name: annotations
Classes/AWSComprehendDatasetEntityRecogn.abstract: The S3 location of the annotation documents for your custom entity recognizer.

Classes/AWSComprehendDatasetEntityRecogn.name: documents
Classes/AWSComprehendDatasetEntityRecogn.abstract: The format and location of the training documents for your custom entity recognizer.

Classes/AWSComprehendDatasetEntityRecogn.name: entityList
Classes/AWSComprehendDatasetEntityRecogn.abstract: The S3 location of the entity list for your custom entity recognizer.

Classes/AWSComprehendDatasetEntityRecogn.name: s3Uri
Classes/AWSComprehendDatasetEntityRecogn.abstract: Specifies the Amazon S3 location where the entity list is located.

Classes/AWSComprehendDatasetEntityRecogn.name: inputFormat
Classes/AWSComprehendDatasetEntityRecogn.abstract: Specifies how the text in an input file should be processed. This is optional, and the default is ONE_DOC_PER_LINE. ONE_DOC_PER_FILE - Each file is considered a separate document. Use this option when you are processing large documents, such as newspaper articles or scientific papers. ONE_DOC_PER_LINE - Each line in a file is considered a separate document. Use this option when you are processing many short documents, such as text messages.

Classes/AWSComprehendDatasetEntityRecogn.name: s3Uri
Classes/AWSComprehendDatasetEntityRecogn.abstract: Specifies the Amazon S3 location where the documents for the dataset are located.

Classes/AWSComprehendDatasetEntityRecogn.name: s3Uri
Classes/AWSComprehendDatasetEntityRecogn.abstract: Specifies the Amazon S3 location where the training documents for an entity recognizer are located. The URI must be in the same Region as the API endpoint that you are calling.

Classes/AWSComprehendDatasetDocumentClas.name: labelDelimiter
Classes/AWSComprehendDatasetDocumentClas.abstract: Indicates the delimiter used to separate each label for training a multi-label classifier. The default delimiter between labels is a pipe (|). You can use a different character as a delimiter (if it’s an allowed character) by specifying it under Delimiter for labels. If the training documents use a delimiter other than the default or the delimiter you specify, the labels on that line will be combined to make a single unique label, such as LABELLABELLABEL.

Classes/AWSComprehendDatasetDocumentClas.name: s3Uri
Classes/AWSComprehendDatasetDocumentClas.abstract:
The Amazon S3 URI for the input data. The S3 bucket must be in the same Region as the API endpoint that you are calling. The URI can point to a single input file or it can provide the prefix for a collection of input files.

For example, if you use the URI S3://bucketName/prefix, if the prefix is a single file, Amazon Comprehend uses that file as input. If more than one file begins with the prefix, Amazon Comprehend uses all of them as input.

This parameter is required if you set DataFormat to COMPREHEND_CSV.

Classes/AWSComprehendDatasetAugmentedMan.name: annotationDataS3Uri
Classes/AWSComprehendDatasetAugmentedMan.abstract: The S3 prefix to the annotation files that are referred in the augmented manifest file.

Classes/AWSComprehendDatasetAugmentedMan.name: attributeNames
Classes/AWSComprehendDatasetAugmentedMan.abstract:
The JSON attribute that contains the annotations for your training documents. The number of attribute names that you specify depends on whether your augmented manifest file is the output of a single labeling job or a chained labeling job.

If your file is the output of a single labeling job, specify the LabelAttributeName key that was used when the job was created in Ground Truth.

If your file is the output of a chained labeling job, specify the LabelAttributeName key for one or more jobs in the chain. Each LabelAttributeName key provides the annotations from an individual job.

Classes/AWSComprehendDatasetAugmentedMan.name: documentType
Classes/AWSComprehendDatasetAugmentedMan.abstract:
The type of augmented manifest. If you don’t specify, the default is PlainTextDocument.

PLAIN_TEXT_DOCUMENT A document type that represents any unicode text that is encoded in UTF-8.

Classes/AWSComprehendDatasetAugmentedMan.name: s3Uri
Classes/AWSComprehendDatasetAugmentedMan.abstract: The Amazon S3 location of the augmented manifest file.

Classes/AWSComprehendDatasetAugmentedMan.name: sourceDocumentsS3Uri
Classes/AWSComprehendDatasetAugmentedMan.abstract: The S3 prefix to the source files (PDFs) that are referred to in the augmented manifest file.

ID for the KMS key that Amazon Comprehend uses to encrypt trained custom models. The ModelKmsKeyId can be either of the following formats:

  • Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of a KMS Key: "arn:aws:kms:us-west-2:111122223333:key/1234abcd-12ab-34cd-56ef-1234567890ab"

Classes/AWSComprehendDataSecurityConfig..name: volumeKmsKeyId
Classes/AWSComprehendDataSecurityConfig..abstract: ID for the KMS key that Amazon Comprehend uses to encrypt the volume.

Classes/AWSComprehendDataSecurityConfig..name: vpcConfig
Classes/AWSComprehendDataSecurityConfig..abstract: Configuration parameters for an optional private Virtual Private Cloud (VPC) containing the resources you are using for the job. For more information, see Amazon VPC.

Classes/AWSComprehendCreateFlywheelReque.name: clientRequestToken
Classes/AWSComprehendCreateFlywheelReque.abstract: A unique identifier for the request. If you don’t set the client request token, Amazon Comprehend generates one.

Classes/AWSComprehendCreateFlywheelReque.name: dataAccessRoleArn
Classes/AWSComprehendCreateFlywheelReque.abstract: The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the IAM role that grants Amazon Comprehend the permissions required to access the flywheel data in the data lake.

Classes/AWSComprehendCreateFlywheelReque.name: dataLakeS3Uri
Classes/AWSComprehendCreateFlywheelReque.abstract: Enter the S3 location for the data lake. You can specify a new S3 bucket or a new folder of an existing S3 bucket. The flywheel creates the data lake at this location.

Classes/AWSComprehendCreateEntityRecogni.name: clientRequestToken

Classes/AWSComprehendCreateEntityRecogni.name: dataAccessRoleArn
Classes/AWSComprehendCreateEntityRecogni.abstract: The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the IAM role that grants Amazon Comprehend read access to your input data.

Classes/AWSComprehendCreateEntityRecogni.name: inputDataConfig
Classes/AWSComprehendCreateEntityRecogni.abstract: Specifies the format and location of the input data. The S3 bucket containing the input data must be located in the same Region as the entity recognizer being created.

Classes/AWSComprehendCreateEntityRecogni.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSComprehendCreateEntityRecogni.abstract: You can specify any of the following languages: English (“en”), Spanish (“es”), French (“fr”), Italian (“it”), German (“de”), or Portuguese (“pt”). If you plan to use this entity recognizer with PDF, Word, or image input files, you must specify English as the language. All training documents must be in the same language.

Classes/AWSComprehendCreateEntityRecogni.name: modelKmsKeyId
Classes/AWSComprehendCreateEntityRecogni.abstract:
ID for the KMS key that Amazon Comprehend uses to encrypt trained custom models. The ModelKmsKeyId can be either of the following formats:

  • KMS Key ID: "1234abcd-12ab-34cd-56ef-1234567890ab"

  • Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of a KMS Key: "arn:aws:kms:us-west-2:111122223333:key/1234abcd-12ab-34cd-56ef-1234567890ab"

Classes/AWSComprehendCreateEntityRecogni.name: modelPolicy
Classes/AWSComprehendCreateEntityRecogni.abstract:
The JSON resource-based policy to attach to your custom entity recognizer model. You can use this policy to allow another Amazon Web Services account to import your custom model.

Provide your JSON as a UTF-8 encoded string without line breaks. To provide valid JSON for your policy, enclose the attribute names and values in double quotes. If the JSON body is also enclosed in double quotes, then you must escape the double quotes that are inside the policy:

"{\"attribute\": \"value\", \"attribute\": [\"value\"]}"

To avoid escaping quotes, you can use single quotes to enclose the policy and double quotes to enclose the JSON names and values:

'{"attribute": "value", "attribute": ["value"]}'

Classes/AWSComprehendCreateEntityRecogni.name: recognizerName
Classes/AWSComprehendCreateEntityRecogni.abstract: The name given to the newly created recognizer. Recognizer names can be a maximum of 256 characters. Alphanumeric characters, hyphens (-) and underscores (_) are allowed. The name must be unique in the account/Region.

Classes/AWSComprehendCreateEntityRecogni.name: tags
Classes/AWSComprehendCreateEntityRecogni.abstract: Tags to associate with the entity recognizer. A tag is a key-value pair that adds as a metadata to a resource used by Amazon Comprehend. For example, a tag with “Sales” as the key might be added to a resource to indicate its use by the sales department.

Classes/AWSComprehendCreateEntityRecogni.name: versionName
Classes/AWSComprehendCreateEntityRecogni.abstract: The version name given to the newly created recognizer. Version names can be a maximum of 256 characters. Alphanumeric characters, hyphens (-) and underscores (_) are allowed. The version name must be unique among all models with the same recognizer name in the account/Region.

Classes/AWSComprehendCreateEntityRecogni.name: volumeKmsKeyId

ID for the Amazon Web Services Key Management Service (KMS) key that Amazon Comprehend uses to encrypt data on the storage volume attached to the ML compute instance(s) that process the analysis job. The VolumeKmsKeyId can be either of the following formats:

  • KMS Key ID: "1234abcd-12ab-34cd-56ef-1234567890ab"

  • Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of a KMS Key: "arn:aws:kms:us-west-2:111122223333:key/1234abcd-12ab-34cd-56ef-1234567890ab"

Classes/AWSComprehendCreateEntityRecogni.name: vpcConfig
Classes/AWSComprehendCreateEntityRecogni.abstract: Configuration parameters for an optional private Virtual Private Cloud (VPC) containing the resources you are using for your custom entity recognizer. For more information, see Amazon VPC.

Classes/AWSComprehendCreateEndpointReque.name: clientRequestToken

Classes/AWSComprehendCreateEndpointReque.name: dataAccessRoleArn
Classes/AWSComprehendCreateEndpointReque.abstract: The Amazon Resource Name (ARN) of the IAM role that grants Amazon Comprehend read access to trained custom models encrypted with a customer managed key (ModelKmsKeyId).

Classes/AWSComprehendCreateEndpointReque.name: desiredInferenceUnits
Classes/AWSComprehendCreateEndpointReque.abstract: The desired number of inference units to be used by the model using this endpoint. Each inference unit represents of a throughput of 100 characters per second.

Classes/AWSComprehendCreateEndpointReque.name: endpointName

Classes/AWSComprehendCreateEndpointReque.name: flywheelArn

Classes/AWSComprehendCreateEndpointReque.name: modelArn
Classes/AWSComprehendCreateEndpointReque.abstract: The Amazon Resource Number (ARN) of the model to which the endpoint will be attached.

Classes/AWSComprehendCreateEndpointReque.name: tags
Classes/AWSComprehendCreateEndpointReque.abstract: Tags to associate with the endpoint. A tag is a key-value pair that adds metadata to the endpoint. For example, a tag with “Sales” as the key might be added to an endpoint to indicate its use by the sales department.

Classes/AWSComprehendCreateDocumentClass.name: dataAccessRoleArn

Classes/AWSComprehendCreateDocumentClass.name: inputDataConfig

Classes/AWSComprehendCreateDocumentClass.name: languageCode

Classes/AWSComprehendCreateDocumentClass.name: mode
Classes/AWSComprehendCreateDocumentClass.abstract: Indicates the mode in which the classifier will be trained. The classifier can be trained in multi-class mode, which identifies one and only one class for each document, or multi-label mode, which identifies one or more labels for each document. In multi-label mode, multiple labels for an individual document are separated by a delimiter. The default delimiter between labels is a pipe (|).

Classes/AWSComprehendCreateDocumentClass.name: modelKmsKeyId

Classes/AWSComprehendCreateDocumentClass.name: modelPolicy
Classes/AWSComprehendCreateDocumentClass.abstract:
The resource-based policy to attach to your custom document classifier model. You can use this policy to allow another Amazon Web Services account to import your custom model.

"{\"attribute\": \"value\", \"attribute\": [\"value\"]}"

To avoid escaping quotes, you can use single quotes to enclose the policy and double quotes to enclose the JSON names and values:

'{"attribute": "value", "attribute": ["value"]}'

Classes/AWSComprehendCreateDocumentClass.name: outputDataConfig
Classes/AWSComprehendCreateDocumentClass.abstract: Specifies the location for the output files from a custom classifier job. This parameter is required for a request that creates a native classifier model.

Classes/AWSComprehendCreateDocumentClass.name: tags

Classes/AWSComprehendCreateDocumentClass.name: versionName

Classes/AWSComprehendCreateDatasetReques.name: clientRequestToken
Classes/AWSComprehendCreateDatasetReques.abstract: A unique identifier for the request. If you don’t set the client request token, Amazon Comprehend generates one.

Classes/AWSComprehendCreateDatasetReques.name: datasetType
Classes/AWSComprehendCreateDatasetReques.abstract: The dataset type. You can specify that the data in a dataset is for training the model or for testing the model.

Classes/AWSComprehendCreateDatasetReques.name: flywheelArn
Classes/AWSComprehendCreateDatasetReques.abstract: The Amazon Resource Number (ARN) of the flywheel of the flywheel to receive the data.

Classes/AWSComprehendCreateDatasetReques.name: inputDataConfig
Classes/AWSComprehendCreateDatasetReques.abstract: Information about the input data configuration. The type of input data varies based on the format of the input and whether the data is for a classifier model or an entity recognition model.

Classes/AWSComprehendContainsPiiEntities.name: labels
Classes/AWSComprehendContainsPiiEntities.abstract: The labels used in the document being analyzed. Individual labels represent personally identifiable information (PII) entity types.

Classes/AWSComprehendContainsPiiEntities.name: languageCode
Classes/AWSComprehendContainsPiiEntities.abstract: The language of the input documents. Currently, English is the only valid language.

Classes/AWSComprehendContainsPiiEntities.name: text
Classes/AWSComprehendContainsPiiEntities.abstract: A UTF-8 text string. The maximum string size is 100 KB.

Classes/AWSComprehendClassifyDocumentRes.name: classes
Classes/AWSComprehendClassifyDocumentRes.abstract: The classes used by the document being analyzed. These are used for multi-class trained models. Individual classes are mutually exclusive and each document is expected to have only a single class assigned to it. For example, an animal can be a dog or a cat, but not both at the same time.

Classes/AWSComprehendClassifyDocumentRes.name: documentMetadata
Classes/AWSComprehendClassifyDocumentRes.abstract: Extraction information about the document. This field is present in the response only if your request includes the Byte parameter.

Classes/AWSComprehendClassifyDocumentRes.name: documentType
Classes/AWSComprehendClassifyDocumentRes.abstract: The document type for each page in the input document. This field is present in the response only if your request includes the Byte parameter.

Classes/AWSComprehendClassifyDocumentRes.name: errors
Classes/AWSComprehendClassifyDocumentRes.abstract: Page-level errors that the system detected while processing the input document. The field is empty if the system encountered no errors.

Classes/AWSComprehendClassifyDocumentRes.name: labels
Classes/AWSComprehendClassifyDocumentRes.abstract: The labels used the document being analyzed. These are used for multi-label trained models. Individual labels represent different categories that are related in some manner and are not mutually exclusive. For example, a movie can be just an action movie, or it can be an action movie, a science fiction movie, and a comedy, all at the same time.

Classes/AWSComprehendClassifyDocumentRes.name: warnings
Classes/AWSComprehendClassifyDocumentRes.abstract:
Warnings detected while processing the input document. The response includes a warning if there is a mismatch between the input document type and the model type associated with the endpoint that you specified. The response can also include warnings for individual pages that have a mismatch.

The field is empty if the system generated no warnings.

Classes/AWSComprehendClassifyDocumentReq.name: bytes
Classes/AWSComprehendClassifyDocumentReq.abstract:
Use the Bytes parameter to input a text, PDF, Word or image file. You can also use the Bytes parameter to input an Amazon Textract DetectDocumentText or AnalyzeDocument output file.

Provide the input document as a sequence of base64-encoded bytes. If your code uses an Amazon Web Services SDK to classify documents, the SDK may encode the document file bytes for you.

The maximum length of this field depends on the input document type. For details, see Inputs for real-time custom analysis in the Comprehend Developer Guide.

If you use the Bytes parameter, do not use the Text parameter.

Classes/AWSComprehendClassifyDocumentReq.name: documentReaderConfig
Classes/AWSComprehendClassifyDocumentReq.abstract: Provides configuration parameters to override the default actions for extracting text from PDF documents and image files.

Classes/AWSComprehendClassifyDocumentReq.name: endpointArn
Classes/AWSComprehendClassifyDocumentReq.abstract: The Amazon Resource Number (ARN) of the endpoint. For information about endpoints, see Managing endpoints.

Classes/AWSComprehendClassifyDocumentReq.name: text
Classes/AWSComprehendClassifyDocumentReq.abstract: The document text to be analyzed. If you enter text using this parameter, do not use the Bytes parameter.

Classes/AWSComprehendClassifierMetadata..name: evaluationMetrics
Classes/AWSComprehendClassifierMetadata..abstract: Describes the result metrics for the test data associated with an documentation classifier.

Classes/AWSComprehendClassifierMetadata..name: numberOfLabels
Classes/AWSComprehendClassifierMetadata..abstract: The number of labels in the input data.

Classes/AWSComprehendClassifierMetadata..name: numberOfTestDocuments
Classes/AWSComprehendClassifierMetadata..abstract: The number of documents in the input data that were used to test the classifier. Typically this is 10 to 20 percent of the input documents, up to 10,000 documents.

Classes/AWSComprehendClassifierMetadata..name: numberOfTrainedDocuments
Classes/AWSComprehendClassifierMetadata..abstract: The number of documents in the input data that were used to train the classifier. Typically this is 80 to 90 percent of the input documents.

Classes/AWSComprehendClassifierEvaluatio.name: accuracy
Classes/AWSComprehendClassifierEvaluatio.abstract: The fraction of the labels that were correct recognized. It is computed by dividing the number of labels in the test documents that were correctly recognized by the total number of labels in the test documents.

Classes/AWSComprehendClassifierEvaluatio.name: f1Score
Classes/AWSComprehendClassifierEvaluatio.abstract: A measure of how accurate the classifier results are for the test data. It is derived from the Precision and Recall values. The F1Score is the harmonic average of the two scores. The highest score is 1, and the worst score is 0.

Classes/AWSComprehendClassifierEvaluatio.name: hammingLoss
Classes/AWSComprehendClassifierEvaluatio.abstract: Indicates the fraction of labels that are incorrectly predicted. Also seen as the fraction of wrong labels compared to the total number of labels. Scores closer to zero are better.

Classes/AWSComprehendClassifierEvaluatio.name: microF1Score
Classes/AWSComprehendClassifierEvaluatio.abstract: A measure of how accurate the classifier results are for the test data. It is a combination of the Micro Precision and Micro Recall values. The Micro F1Score is the harmonic mean of the two scores. The highest score is 1, and the worst score is 0.

Classes/AWSComprehendClassifierEvaluatio.name: microPrecision
Classes/AWSComprehendClassifierEvaluatio.abstract: A measure of the usefulness of the recognizer results in the test data. High precision means that the recognizer returned substantially more relevant results than irrelevant ones. Unlike the Precision metric which comes from averaging the precision of all available labels, this is based on the overall score of all precision scores added together.

Classes/AWSComprehendClassifierEvaluatio.name: microRecall
Classes/AWSComprehendClassifierEvaluatio.abstract: A measure of how complete the classifier results are for the test data. High recall means that the classifier returned most of the relevant results. Specifically, this indicates how many of the correct categories in the text that the model can predict. It is a percentage of correct categories in the text that can found. Instead of averaging the recall scores of all labels (as with Recall), micro Recall is based on the overall score of all recall scores added together.

Classes/AWSComprehendClassifierEvaluatio.name: precision
Classes/AWSComprehendClassifierEvaluatio.abstract: A measure of the usefulness of the classifier results in the test data. High precision means that the classifier returned substantially more relevant results than irrelevant ones.

Classes/AWSComprehendClassifierEvaluatio.name: recall
Classes/AWSComprehendClassifierEvaluatio.abstract: A measure of how complete the classifier results are for the test data. High recall means that the classifier returned most of the relevant results.

Classes/AWSComprehendAugmentedManifestsL.name: attributeNames
Classes/AWSComprehendAugmentedManifestsL.abstract:
The JSON attribute that contains the annotations for your training documents. The number of attribute names that you specify depends on whether your augmented manifest file is the output of a single labeling job or a chained labeling job.

Classes/AWSComprehendDocumentReaderConfi.abstract:
Provides configuration parameters to override the default actions for extracting text from PDF documents and image files.

By default, Amazon Comprehend performs the following actions to extract text from files, based on the input file type:

  • Word files - Amazon Comprehend parser extracts the text.

  • Digital PDF files - Amazon Comprehend parser extracts the text.

  • Image files and scanned PDF files - Amazon Comprehend uses the Amazon Textract DetectDocumentText API to extract the text.

DocumentReaderConfig does not apply to plain text files or Word files.

For image files and PDF documents, you can override these default actions using the fields listed below. For more information, see Setting text extraction options in the Comprehend Developer Guide.

Text extraction encountered one or more page-level errors in the input document.

The ErrorCode contains one of the following values:

  • TEXTRACT_BAD_PAGE - Amazon Textract cannot read the page. For more information about page limits in Amazon Textract, see Page Quotas in Amazon Textract.

  • TEXTRACT_PROVISIONED_THROUGHPUT_EXCEEDED - The number of requests exceeded your throughput limit. For more information about throughput quotas in Amazon Textract, see Default quotas in Amazon Textract.

  • PAGE_CHARACTERS_EXCEEDED - Too many text characters on the page (10,000 characters maximum).

  • PAGE_SIZE_EXCEEDED - The maximum page size is 10 MB.

  • INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR - The request encountered a service issue. Try the API request again.
